Benchmark for designing and developing the National Edition of Aldo Moro's works¶

Executive summary¶

This work aims to define a series of reference models that would serve as a guide to the design and development of the National Edition of Aldo Moro's works. These models have been defined through a benchmarking process that is organized as follows:

  • content analysis on a sample of 30 digital editions, evaluated on the basis of certain criteria defined in Sahle 2014;
  • processing of the data gathered as a result of the content analysis, so as to extract the relevant information, and visualize it;
  • review of the data processing results and consideration of the models that can be used as reference.

The digital editions that meet the quality criteria taken into consideration are equipped with the following characteristics: their audience is composed of both domain experts and generic users; their documentation is rich and accurate; their content is described by a complete set of metadata; they and their single parts are citable and uniquely identifiable; their data model is geared towards interoperability and interlinking between its contents and the relevant resources already existing on the Web; they use visualization and storytelling tools so as to convey information intuitively; their information architecture is well-structured and easily navigated; their data and contents can be downloaded in many different formats; they take advantage of Open Source software and tools; finally, their contents are open and accessible to anyone.

The Main findings section offers a high-level overview on the results of the data processing. The procedure of data gathering, processing and visualization is explained in the Methodology section. Finally, in the Conclusions section, a series of digital editions are proposed to be reference models for our edition.

Main findings¶

The results of the data processing are the following:

  • high-quality digital editions tend to have a composite and diverse audience;
  • documentation tends to be considered a relevant editorial product, although it is often incomplete, loosely organized, and/or without a clear way to cite it. Metadata are fundamental elements of the edition that are generally taken into great consideration, yet their use could be further optimized - especially in terms of interlinking the contents of the edition to each other and to the related resources on the Web. Permanent identification and citation are considered to be relatively important;
  • the potentialities offered by digital technologies in terms of textual representation are recognized by a respectable number of digital editions. XML-TEI is the preferred standard, while RDF and other models are still underused. Alternative ways to make contact with the edition's data and contents, such as storytelling and visualizations, are also not fully exploited; when they are implemented, such functionalities might be interesting, but often project-dependent;
  • information architecture is seldom taken into account. On the contrary, great attention has been put in the search system, often optimized through the use of boolean operators or faceted navigation that allow filtering results according to specific criteria. Indexes are commonly used tools that make content navigation more intuitive and structured;
  • another problem is represented by the lack of formats in which data and contents of the edition are published, downloaded, and shared;
  • on the one hand, digital editions are generally open for consultation, and developed by taking advantage of Open Source software; on the other, they tend to be subject to restrictive policies when it comes to Open Access and reuse.

Methodology¶

Data collection¶

The evaluation criteria that have been used to review the sample are based on part of the criteria for reviewing scholarly digital editions compiled by Patrick Sahle in collaboration with Georg Voegler and IDE (Institut fr Dokumentologie und Editorik) members (Sahle 2014). In particular, the aspects that have been taken into consideration during the evaluation process are the following:

  • Documentation (Documentation, Scholarly objectives, Mission focusing on the objectives, Documentation and associated texts);
  • Audience (Mission, focusing on the audience);
  • Representation (Representation of documents and texts);
  • Data model (Data modelling);
  • Browse;
  • Search;
  • Indices;
  • Quality of the presentation;
  • Metadata (Metadata for description of and interlinkage between objects in the edition);
  • Identification (Identification and citation);
  • Formats (Spin offs and export formats);
  • OS-OA (Access to basic data, Rights and licences);
  • Additional features;

Each aspect (except for Audience and Data model) has been given a score between 0, 0.5, and 1, where:

  • 0 represents a value that witnesses either the total absence or the lack of quality of the edition in terms of that specific aspect;
  • 0.5 represents a value that witnesses a suboptimal implementation of that specific aspect in the edition;
  • 1 represents a value that witnesses an optimal implementation of that specific aspect in the edition.

The values associated with each aspect of each edition, along with its title and URL, have been collected in a CSV dataset (benchmark-moro.csv), in which each row represents a digital edition and each column represents one of its aspects.

Define the function for plotting the data¶

In [165]:
def plot_data(data, x_label, colors, plot_title):
    sns.set_style("white")
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    g = sns.countplot(data=data, x=x_label, palette=colors)
    ax=g
    for p in ax.patches:
        if p == ax.patches[0]:
            ax.annotate("%.0f" % p.get_height(), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                     ha='center', va='center', fontsize=25, color=colors[0], xytext=(0, 20),
                     textcoords='offset points')
        elif p == ax.patches[1]:
            ax.annotate("%.0f" % p.get_height(), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                     ha='center', va='center', fontsize=25, color=colors[1], xytext=(0, 20),
                     textcoords='offset points')
        elif p == ax.patches[2]:
            ax.annotate("%.0f" % p.get_height(), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                     ha='center', va='center', fontsize=25, color=colors[2], xytext=(0, 20),
                     textcoords='offset points')
        else:
            ax.annotate("%.0f" % p.get_height(), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                     ha='center', va='center', fontsize=25, color=colors[3], xytext=(0, 20),
                     textcoords='offset points')
    _ = g.set_ylim(0,25)
    g.set(yticks=[])
    sns.despine(left=True)
    ax.set_xlabel(x_label)
    ax.set_ylabel('')
    plt.title(plot_title, fontsize=20, y=-0.25)

Category: Objective and methods¶

A digital edition should provide an accurate description of its methodology, editorial principles, transcription and markup guidelines, and mission.

A first look at the data suggests that in terms of Documentation and Representation, the digital editions' quality tends to be pretty high. Moreover, it is possible to notice that the majority of digital editions taken into consideration has a heterogeneous audience, composed of specialists and laymen alike, and tends to be based on XML-TEI.

Documentation¶

In [159]:
plot_data(data, 'documentation', ['lightgrey', 'orange', 'green'], 'Most editions are either fully or partly documented')

The values have been assigned according the following criteria:

  • 0: documentation is non-existent or insufficient;
  • 0.5: documentation is partial and contains superficial information about the project, its contents, and its technical implementation;
  • 1: documentation is complete and contains detailed information about the project, its contents, and its technical implementation.

Audience¶

In [147]:
plot_data(data, 'audience', ['lightgray', 'purple', 'lightgray', 'lightgray'], 'Most editions address a composite audience')

The values have been assigned according the following criteria:

  • ns: not specified;
  • specialist: domain experts, such as researchers, scholars, etc.;
  • general: laymen;
  • both: both domain experts and laymen.

Representation¶

In [148]:
plot_data(data, 'text-representation', ['lightgray', 'orange', 'lightgray'], 'Most editions provide a medium-quality representation of documents')

The values have been assigned according the following criteria:

  • 0: documents' representation is low-quality;
  • 0.5: documents' representation is average;
  • 1: documents' representation is high-quality.

Data model¶

In [149]:
plot_data(data, 'data-model', ['purple', 'lightgray', 'lightgray'], 'Most editions model their data according to XML-TEI')

The values have been assigned according the following criteria:

  • TEI: the digital edition's data model follows the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) Guidelines;
  • RDF: the digital edition's data model is based on the Resource Description Framework (RDF);
  • other: the digital edition's data model is based on a different schema.

Category: Publication and presentation¶

A digital edition must publish clear, complete, usable and browsable materials. On a first glance, it is possible to notice that data distribution is less uniform. Three aspects that are strongly interconnected, such as Browse, Search, and Indices, present different and unexpected results. Other aspects, which follow more positive trends, are Quality of the presentation, Metadata, and Identification: in general, digital editions are identified by bibliographic citations and persistent identifiers (DOI, ISBN, etc.) and expose their materials accompanied with adequate metadata. Aspects that instead follow generally negative trends are Formats, and Additional features: in general, digital editions are not equipped with multiple download formats, nor additional functionalities for exposing and using data. Finally, with regards to Open Source e Open Access, most editions use Open Source software, but do not publish their contents with an Open Access license.

Identification¶

The values have been assigned according the following criteria:

  • 0.5: the digital edition may have permanent identifiers at the highest levels of granularity and may provide a suggestion for its citation model;

Open Source and Open Access¶

In [166]:
plot_data(data, 'os-oa', ['lightgray', 'orange', 'lightgray'], 'Most editions can be Open Source, and their contents \nare freely accessible, but not reusable')

The values have been assigned according the following criteria:

  • 0: the software used to develop the digital edition is not Open Source. The edition's contents cannot be reused by other researchers; in order to access them, the users have to sign in and sometimes pay a subscription fee;
  • 0.5: the software used to develop the digital edition can be Open Source. The edition's contents are freely accessible, but not reusable;
  • 1: the software used to develop the digital edition is Open Source. The edition's contents are freely accessible and reusable.

Define the function to visualize the characteristics of the selected models¶

In [86]:
labels = ['documentation', 'text-representation', 'browse', 'search', 'indices', 'presentation-quality', 'metadata', 'identification', 'formats', 'os-oa', 'add-features']

def generate_radar(title):
    values = data_final_2.loc[title].tolist()
    num_vars = len(labels)

    angles = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, num_vars, endpoint=False).tolist()

    values += values[:1]
    angles += angles[:1]

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 6), subplot_kw=dict(polar=True))

    ax.plot(angles, values, color='#1aaf6c', linewidth=1)
    ax.fill(angles, values, color='lightgreen', alpha=0.25)

    ax.set_theta_offset(np.pi / 2)
    ax.set_theta_direction(-1)

    ax.set_thetagrids(np.degrees(angles), labels)

    for label, angle in zip(ax.get_xticklabels(), angles):
      if angle in (0, np.pi):
        label.set_horizontalalignment('center')
      elif 0 < angle < np.pi:
        label.set_horizontalalignment('left')
      else:
        label.set_horizontalalignment('right')

    ax.set_rgrids([0, 0.5, 1])

    ax.set_rlabel_position(180 / num_vars)

    ax.tick_params(colors='#222222')
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=8)
    ax.grid(color='#AAAAAA')
    ax.spines['polar'].set_color('#222222')
    ax.set_facecolor('#FAFAFA')
    
    ax.set_title(title, y=1.08)
